  "year": 2021,
  "DOI": "10.1116/6.0000722",
  "summary": "This paper presents a strategy for topographically selective atomic layer deposition (ALD) in which a thin amorphous-carbon (a-C) film is used as an inhibition layer. Because common ALD precursors nucleate very slowly on a-C, coating the field region with this layer while leaving the interiors of etched trenches carbon-free confines ALD growth to the recessed features. The authors demonstrate selective deposition of Al2O3 and TiO2 inside sub-50 nm, high-aspect-ratio trenches, achieving void-free gap fill while effectively suppressing film growth on the top surface. The work systematically examines inhibitor thickness, ALD temperature, and cycle number, and shows that the approach can be integrated into semiconductor process flows for self-aligned, bottom-up deposition of functional thin films."
