{
  "authors": ["Mengjie Xia", "Xiaohui Liu", "Wei Chen", "Jianguo Wang", "Zhongwei Chen"],
  "year": 2021,
  "DOI": "10.1021/acs.chemrev.1c00329",
  "summary": "This review discusses how atomic layer deposition (ALD) can be utilized to build and fine-tune catalysts at the atomic scale for electrochemical energy-conversion and energy-storage systems. It details strategies for depositing ultrathin oxides, metals, nitrides, and sulfides with sub-nanometer precision, creating well-defined active sites, protecting electrodes, and engineering complex heterointerfaces. The paper correlates ALD-controlled structures with catalytic performance through in-situ/operando spectroscopy and theoretical modeling, highlights representative advances in water splitting, fuel cells, metal–air batteries, and lithium-ion batteries, and outlines future opportunities and challenges for integrating ALD-derived catalysts into practical devices."
}

{
  "authors": ["Yuan Xiao", "Fanqiang Meng", "Wen Shi", "Mijin Kim", "W. M. M. Kessels"],
  "year": 2022,
  "DOI": "10.1002/aenm.202102783",
  "summary": "This review article surveys the state-of-the-art in spatial atomic layer deposition (s-ALD) and how it is being scaled up for next-generation energy-conversion and electronic devices. After outlining the fundamental differences between spatial and temporal ALD, the paper discusses reactor architectures (rotary, linear, and roll-to-roll systems), precursor delivery strategies, and growth kinetics at atmospheric and low pressure. It then details how s-ALD is enabling high-throughput fabrication of thin films for photovoltaics, solid-state batteries, electrochromic windows, thermoelectrics, thin-film transistors, sensors, and flexible electronics. Particular emphasis is placed on conformality over large areas, reduced cost-of-ownership compared with conventional ALD, and the remaining challenges such as precursor utilization efficiency, parasitic CVD, and temperature-window limitations. The authors conclude with an outlook on integrating s-ALD into industrial production lines and combining it with other spatially separated vapor-phase techniques for hybrid manufacturing."
}
